{
  "_comment": [
    "Closed classes: personal pronouns, demonstratives, existentials, and (regular)",
    "interrogatives. The `irregular` rows are fully-enumerated surface forms consulted by",
    "the analyzer BEFORE the FSM (source=lexicon, dictionary-verified).",
    "",
    "Design decisions:",
    "- Personal pronouns decline suppletively (bana/sana datives, pronominal -n- of onu/onda,",
    "  genitive-based instrumentals benimle/seninle/onunla/bununla). They are NOT added as",
    "  regular Roots: a Root ben would license *bene/*benler and misparse benim as poss_1sg.",
    "- onlar lemmatizes to 'o' (UD convention: onlar = o + lar), number=plural, person=3pl.",
    "- The o / onlar paradigm carries NO pron_type: its surface is genuinely ambiguous",
    "  between the personal and the demonstrative reading, so we do not fabricate one.",
    "- bu / şu carry pron_type=demonstrative.",
    "- The colloquial PERSONAL instrumentals benle/senle ARE enumerated (source=lexicon),",
    "  each flagged register=colloquial, alongside their standard twins benimle/seninle (no",
    "  register flag) — the pair documents the variant split. This is the variants pass the",
    "  earlier standard-only note deferred; it is a closed, listable addition, not a rule.",
    "- Still excluded: the DEMONSTRATIVE colloquial bunla/şunla and the personal-o colloquial",
    "  onla (correctness over coverage); onla additionally reads as on(NUM)+la 'with ten', so a",
    "  demonstrative/o colloquial reading is left to a later pass rather than fabricated here.",
    "- var / yok are exact bare forms only (pos=ADJ, existential=true), never Roots, so the",
    "  FSM can never inflect them into junk like *varda/*varlar. Copular vardı/yoktu/varmış",
    "  belong to the later nominal-copula milestone.",
    "- Interrogatives kim / nere decline regularly and so live under `entries` (kime, kimde,",
    "  nerede, nereye all fall out of the FSM); only the genitive-based instrumental kiminle",
    "  is irregular and enumerated here."
  ],

